result.execSummary:
The defendant Steven E. Strey Sr. was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Bail Jumping-Felony, a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 946.49(1)(b).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes: .Bond applied, remaining balance to be paid on a schedule established by the agent.   Defendant is ordered to pay the $250.00 DNA surcharge, provide a sample for testing through the Dept. of Corrections as required in felony convictions.
Defendant shall attend counseling, programming, treatments, evualations as deemed appropriate by the agent releasing all records to the agent upon request

Defendant shall not possess or consume any alcohol, and not go into places that sell alcohol except incidentally such as a grocery store, convenience store or gas station or other such place where alcohol is not sold for consumption on the premises.  
The defendant shall have no contact with James Strey  of any kind, whether direct or indirect, including in person, in writing, by phone, by e-mail or other electronic means, through a third party or in any other way.  Defendant shall not be on or around the premises of 415 Clark Street, Granton WI.
Defendant is not to possess or take any medications unless prescribed by a doctor and they are to be taken as prescribed.  Defendant must execute all releases of information for assessments, counseling, treatment to allow probation agent to verify compliance.

The defendant shall pay Department of Correction fees as directed by the agent.  
The defendant shall submit to random urine testing/PBT's as required by the agent or any law enforcement.

timeConds.notes: Huber granted.  Defendant was granted 43 days credit for time served.
